<subSubSection pageNumber="529" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="529">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="529">Note:</emphasis>
This name had frequently been rejected as a 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="529">nomen dubium</emphasis>
(e.g. by Pedersen in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="529">Darwiniana</emphasis>
17: 438. 1967 and Mears &amp; Gillis in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="529">J. Arnold Arbor.</emphasis>
58: 62. 1977) before Mears (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="529">Taxon</emphasis>
29: 91. 1980) attempted to dispose of the name by typifying it using material in 
<specimenReference collectionCode="BM-SL" pageNumber="529" specimenCode="106">
Herb. Sloane 2: 106 (
<collectionCode pageNumber="529">BM-SL</collectionCode>
)
</specimenReference>
, which he stated would make it a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(L.)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Alternanthera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageNumber="529" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sessilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="529">Alternanthera sessilis</emphasis>
(L.)
</taxonomicName>
DC. However, his chosen type is not the material from which 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sloane’s" pageNumber="529">Sloane's</normalizedToken>
t. 86, f. 2 (which was cited by Linnaeus) was prepared, which is identifiable as 
<taxonomicName authority="A. St." authorityName="A. St." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Alternanthera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageNumber="529" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paronychioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="529">A. paronychioides</emphasis>
A. St.
</taxonomicName>
-Hil. Although 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mears’" pageNumber="529">Mears'</normalizedToken>
intention was laudable, a 
<typeStatus pageNumber="529">neotype</typeStatus>
cannot be designated when original material exists (Art. 9.11). It appears that formal rejection of the name may be necessary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
